"Shaffer G.","Long time management of fossil fuel resources to limit global warming and avoid ice age onsets",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","3", L03704,"","",,,10.1029/2008GL036294,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65249086865&partnerID=40&md5=6d97b1efc07d74401e3473b25ecb8474","Niels Bohr Institute, University of Copenhagen, Copenhagen, Denmark; Departamento de Geofísica, Universidad de Concepción, Concepcion, Chile; Danish Center for Earth System Science, Humlebaek, Denmark; Niels Bohr Institute, University of Copenhagen, Juliane Maries Vej 30, DK-2100 Copenhagen Ø, Denmark","Shaffer, G., Niels Bohr Institute, University of Copenhagen, Copenhagen, Denmark, Departamento de Geofísica, Universidad de Concepción, Concepcion, Chile, Danish Center for Earth System Science, Humlebaek, Denmark, Niels Bohr Institute, University of Copenhagen, Juliane Maries Vej 30, DK-2100 Copenhagen Ø, Denmark","There are about 5000 billion tons of fossil fuel carbon in accessible reserves. Combustion of all this carbon within the next few centuries would force high atmospheric CO2 content and extreme global warming. On the other hand, low atmospheric CO2 content favors the onset of an ice age when changes in the Earth's orbit lead to low summer insolation at high northern latitudes. Here I present Earth System Model projections showing that typical reduction targets for fossil fuel use in the present century could limit ongoing global warming to less than one degree Celcius above present. Furthermore, the projections show that combustion pulses of remaining fossil fuel reserves could then be tailored to raise atmospheric CO2 content high and long enough to parry forcing of ice age onsets by summer insolation minima far into the future. Our present interglacial period could be extended by about 500,000 years in this way. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric CO; Earth system models; Earth's orbits; Fossil fuel resources; Ice ages; Interglacial periods; Northern latitudes; Reduction targets; Time managements; Combustion; Glacial geology; Global warming; Ice; Management; Model structures; Solar radiation; Thermochemistry; Fossil fuels; carbon dioxide; combustion; fossil fuel; global warming; insolation; interglacial; resource management",,,,,,"Archer, D., Fate of fossil fuel CO2 in geologic time (2005) J. Geophys. Res, 11, pp. C09S05. , doi:10.1029/2004JC002625; Archer, D., Ganopolski, A., A moveable trigger: Fossil fuel CO2 and the onset of the next glaciation (2005) Geochem. Geophys. Geosyst, 6, pp. Q05003. , doi:10.1029/2004GC000891; Berger, A., Long-term variations of daily insolation and Quaternary climatic changes (1978) J. Atmos. Sci, 35, pp. 2362-2367; Berger, A., Li, X.S., Loutre, M.F., Modelling Northern Hemisphere ice volume over the last 3 Ma (1999) Quat. Sci. Rev, 18, pp. 1-11; Berner, R.A., Kothavala, Z., GEOCARB BI: A revised model of atmospheric CO2 over Phanerozoic time (2001) Am. J. Sci, 301, pp. 182-204; Calov, R., Ganopolski, A., Multistability and hysteresis in the climate-cryosphere system under orbital forcing (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett, 32, pp. L21717. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024518; Crucifix, M., Loutre, M.F., Berger, A., The climate response to the astronomical forcing (2006) Space Sci. Rev, 125, pp. 213-226; Huybers, P., Wunsch, C., Obliquity pacing of the late Pleistocene glacial terminations (2005) Nature, 434, pp. 491-494; Special Report on Emissions Scenarios (2000) A Special Report of Working Group III of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change IPCC, edited by N. Nakić enović and R. Swart, 599 pp, Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change IPCC, edited by S. D. Solomon et al, 996 pp, Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; La